Tired of small parts breaking loose during printing or large parts warping, and corners lifting off the build plate? Use this snap off ear raft print aid to increase the surface area of parts on your build platform.

Layout the items you want to print in Makerware, then rotate the view so you are looking at your models from underneath. Add the ear raft and copy and paste it as many times as needed. Overlap it with the edges of your model to increase its surface area on the build platform - see the attached images for examples. I tend to space them 10 to 20 mm apart and only overlapping 0.5 to 1 mm seems to work best. 
If you want to slice and print with ReplicatorG you can use Makerware to layout your objects, attach the ear rafts and then export the STL file back to ReplicatorG. Sometimes ReplicatorG/skeinforge will complain but it will print.
This model was derived from an ACIS solid so Makerware, ReplicatorG and Skeinforge have no trouble with it.

remixed_from.title: Cobb AccessPORT holder for Subaru WRX

description.text:
If you have a Cobb AccessPORT on your dash, and the sun is shining bright, you will notice that most of the time, you can't see your screen.
The same issue doesn't happen with your other gauges, or the clock, and that's because there's a visor to shield the sun. This part will snap on to your AccessPORT, and shields the screen from all but direct sunlight.
This part is compatible with reeseallen's AccessPORT holder.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:37769
...and was used to derive this design. A great addition to an awesome dash mount... Let's see the V3 do this!

I printed this part at medium quality (.2mm layer height, 10% infill)
It should just snap right on, but removing it can be a bit tougher; With the AP upside down, and it's back towards you, pulling on the visor from the sides with your fingers and popping the AP out with your thumbs works best.
You can always sand a little off the side nubs, or warm up the part and stretch the sides out to make it easier to put on and remove, but only adjust it a little bit, as it could easily become a sloppy fit if you overdo it.
Be sure to snap this part on first before clipping it into the AP holder. they are a perfect fit together when installed.
If you install your AP on the left-hand side vent, you can rotate it easily, so the longer part of the visor can block incoming sunlight better. I prefer the center vent location, next to the cupholder (in a 04 WRX)
This part will work with V2 and V2B AccessPORTs, regardless of vehicle application.

Oh, and you can always print the parts in ABS, they are much less likely to warp.
I'm in Wisconsin, so it's not as big a deal as being in warmer climates.

Well, strike it up to a lesson learned with a design that didn't work nearly as well as I hoped. This version, unlike the previous one, has a very definite directional bias at higher RPM (10K+ RPM). The top of the blades (the ones on the tapered side of the spindle) are what you want to use as the leading edge. In my print, I took another user's advice and sanded the blades, then hit them with some acetone. I'm not sure how much of a difference this makes, but this fan does seem to move a good amount of air. The blades are a bit thicker, they print out a little better because of this, and they don't seem to flex as much (printed with ABS) as my previous version. There is still a bit of flex when you hit higher RPMs, which might actually be beneficial as the blades could be seeking a more optimal angle of attack. In this design it doesn't seem to affect the blade radius as much when they flex as it did in the previous design. I've gone down to four blades, much wider, with a slightly shallower angle. From what I've been reading, this increases efficiency, though I'm still experimenting to see how good I can get these fan blades to be for my purposes (Expect more versions coming out!).
The pipe fittings I'd promised in my other version are designed, I'll have those up as soon as they are printed and tested. The design is for the motors I've been using (Radio Shack Hi-Speed 9-18VDC motor Part # 2730256). Obligatory Warning
Rotating something at high speed can be dangerous, always be sure to take proper safety precautions such as eye protection, etc to protect against possible failures. Also, take care not to touch the blades during operation. This design has some sharp parts that can cut you (speaking from experience... ouch).

This was printed at 0.1mm layer height, 40% infill, 0.4mm nozzle, 100mm/s, in ABS, on Oni H-Bot, and sliced in Cura. After printing, the blades were sanded a bit, then brushed with acetone to smooth them out a bit.

description.text: My QU-BD extruder was stopping a lot so I made some modifications. The primary problem was the way they push the filament against the drive gear with a set screw. I switched to a spring loaded idler pulley. This will work with the stock QU-BD drive gear, but I switched to an MK7 style drive gear. The extruder is super reliable now. There are two versions of the parts to allow you run the filament through the right side or left side. You need a 4mm I.D. x 13mm O.D x 5mm thk bearing (624), a button head 4mm x 10 screw, a 4mm washer and a spring. I used a 3/8" x 1-1/8" x 0.047 spring from a Home Depot assortment pack. The other parts are available a lot of places, but I bought mine at McMaster Carr. It all fits within the width of the motor, so two can be run side by side. I have a wiki page of all the things I did to tune up my QU-BD extruder here... http://www.buildlog.net/wiki/doku.php?id=ord_bot:qu-bd_extruder_improvements

• Select the version you need depending on what side of the shaft you run your filament through.

  • Print the parts.

  • Use a 3mm drill to clean out the holes.

  • Assembly the lever, bearing, washer and screw. You should be able to "self tap" the screw into the lever.

  • Assemble everything on the extruder except the lever. There is a little bump on the spring block that points towards the motor. This prevents it from rotating.

  • Install the lever with the spring. Hold the spring compressed while installing the screw that goes through the fan, heatsink and lever into the motor. Make sure you don't over-tighten the screw and lock the lever in place.

I have been designing a special part for my current project,
but when i print it, the wobble form the fine infill messes up my print :(
SO:
I created this OpenSCAD program, to test various tube wall thicknesses, to irradiate wobbly infill.
see instructions for more info.
Ceri

first change the OD at the top of OpenSCAD, to suit your needs,
F5, F6, Export STL.
use Slic3r, to make some GCODE,
then view in gcode.ws (free web based gcode viewer )
scan up and down the layers, until you find a wall thickness you like,
with no infill, but no gap !! VERY IMPORTANT
then count the planetary dots, subtract 1,
put that number back into second tube, which is blue.
re-build & slice & view, to make sure,
Use in your models.

description.text:
Probably an unneeded solution to a non-problem.  When I installed the Heated Build Platform on the MakerBot, I ran the cables from the extruder over the top of the bot, down the back to the HBP.  I didn't like the way the cables sat on the z belt.  Instead of running the cables through the inside of the machine, I designed a doohickey to support the cables and protect the belt.
The bottom notch prints just fine for me.  I could have modeled the bottom endcap in place, but I have an almost pathological attraction to symmetry.

Print one bridge and two endcaps.  Cement endcaps into place (I used acetone) and put on the back of your bot where the cables want to go.  If it fits too snugly, you may need to sand out the channel a bit.

title: Alien Jockey Commemorative Bust / Model

description.text:
This commemorative bust is in honour of the late great H.R Giger.
Want to give your printer a workout? Have a resin based printer and want to show what it can do? (I wish i did! :))
The original model, created by the extremely talented Sean Kennedy in Lightwave more than a decade ago.The model was originally designed as an animation backdrop, so alot of parts were single sided and not full meshes, so needed rebuilding manually.. so many polygons... so many, it really was a tricky job. Put it this way, on a machine with 32gigs of Ram, decimating this model crashed Zbrushed several times, which is rare as it performs so well.
Please read the instructions for printing info .

Printing
  • Print the base at 5% infill or more
  • Print the middle section and gun end with less infill than the base
    to keep it balanced.
    Supports and Raft
    Needed!! Not as hard as it looks to remove.
    When removing the support, just don't go hacking at it, be gentle and you should come out ok. I broke one pipe and glued it back, no worries.
    Pieces
    I printed mine in 3 pieces as I wanted a certain size, I have included the Full print, a cut version and a full plate cut version.

it is a matter of a number of variables.
how good is the printer? (this is a really big factor!)
what was the slice (the z)
speed of print can be a factor (slower is typically better for quality
but not necessarilly)
and really a lot of other varibles.
not trying to be obtuse, just letting you know there are many factors.
the short answer is
if i was looking to print this at 1 inch and wanted a good print
i would probably slice at .15
and if the print was not good i would go to the slower replicator default
of 40mm/sec
if you are using a different printer i can't really advise.
but i would highly recomend experimenting to get a good feel for the printer settings.

title: Kenwood Major adapter for Moulinex/Tefal Fresh Express cone cutters

description.text:
I have been a long time and happy user of the Moulinex/Tefal Fresh Express food processor but I recently got a full fledged Kenwood Major kitchen machine. So far I am 100% happy with the Kenwood Major and all the accessories which came with it. So, since I liked the way the fresh express worked, I looked for a similar accessory from Kenwood and was very happy to see that they actually have the "Metal Roto Food Cutter AT643" which seems to do the same thing. So I bought it.

  • Unfortunately, I was disappointed upon the first use. Yes it is all metal, yes it is heavy duty, but NO, it does not shred the carrots the way I want (either it is to fine and a bit mashed or it is too coarse) and NO, NO NO it is not dishwasher safe!!! I found out after putting it in the dishwasher after the first use:-) The metal became dark and ugly. It turns out that the dishwasher soap actually corrodes the alloy it is made of. Really disappointing!!! Another thing I liked about the Fresh Express was how compact it is to store by stacking the blades. Nothing similar with the Kenwood version.

  • Since I cannot have 2 machines/motors on the kitchen bench, all what was left was trying to bridge the compatibility issue between Kenwood and Moullinex/Tefal. It turned out to be quite strait forward since both have at least the same rotation direction :-)

  • This adapter fits the Kenwood Major series and allow attaching the Fresh Express accessory to it (without any modifications). It might work with other Kenwood machine if they use the same socket but I haven't tried. Let me know if it works for you!

I printed the adapted in ABS with 3 perimeters and 30% infill. It seems plenty strong but we will see how durable it actually is.
The axle was printed in PLA also with 3 perimeters and 30% infill (and 100% infill for any area below some threshold)
There is no need for any support or raft. There are 3 built-in supports to be removed on the adapter: 1 for the pin on the Kenwood side at the bottom and 2 thin walls in the socket.

title: Modified laser pointer holder for K40 laser cutter

description.text:
These are modified versions of kai's aiming aid for the K40, the cheap Chinese laser cutter that's all over eBay. Mix & match with the original parts as needed.
  • The holder piece has been modified to fit a 6mm laser diode module I already had, with a swivel mount so that the aim can be adjusted.
  • The hinge piece has been modified to bring the holder about 2mm further out from the mounting clip (the back edge of the lid would otherwise scrape on the holder in my case). Also, I deleted the built-in support fins on this piece, which were causing slicing problems in Cura - the fins were far too thin to actually produce any plastic, yet their presence was keeping Cura from being able to produce any support structure of its own in those areas.
    • The bent piece of metal on the bottom of my holder is simply a weight to make sure that the pointer drops to a consistent position when the lid is opened. This seemed like an easier solution than the spring in the original Thing. My K40 came equipped with a germanium focusing lens, which is completely opaque to visible light. I had to replace it with a ZnSe lens for this accessory to be of any use.

description.text:
Concept design attempt at removing all those nasty smells from my Prusa-Mendal without having to box the entire thing.  Uses a blower fan to suck fumes directly from the extruder nozzle and then exhausts out the nearest window.  
Currently I'm having trouble finding thin walled flexible tubing to connect the nozzle to the fan.  The clear vinyl tube that i'm using right now adds a lot of unwanted force onto the x-carriage.

The exhaust hose is 1-1/4" Drain Pump Hose and the input is 3/4"OD Clear Vinyl tubing.
Everything is designed to be attached with zip ties.
Depending on how long your exhaust pipe is, you may want to use two blower fans in series.

Increasing the length will also help to keep the force low, but will impede air flow (you may want to increase the diameter also, but that may increase the force again, but hopefully not as much)
comments.author: jonathanw

comments.text: Silicone tubing would be great.  I believe the most optimum balance would be a thin walled, 3/4" to 1" ID, spiraled silicone tube.  While a spiral would increase the overall air travel length  it would remove any twisting and prevent pinching.

comments.text:
Well, your tube is already quite fat, flow might not be a problem.
however, maybe the problem is due to the location of the fan: moving the carriage tries to twist the tube (which is hard due to the large diameter, plus the rigidity of vinyl)
Try moving the blower to the end of the z-stage so it's only bending the tube, not twisting it maybe?

comments.text: The location of the fan is definitely the problem.  In order to prevent all twisting it would have to be attached to the X-Carriage but, I was worried about adding the weight. This is a mold for replacement rubber feet such as used on my Kinesis Advantage keyboard. My keyboard was missing one of it's feet which keep it from sliding around the desk. Without this foot the keyboard was not stableâ€”it would rock left-right.
This mold was designed to be used with sugru silicone rubber.
This thing includes the original, positive model and a 4-up mold created using that model (in Blender).

Print the top and bottom cover with a fairly high resolution. The rubber will show all the layers (and imperfections) of the printed surface. Use 3mm filament as pegs to align the top and bottom. Prepare the mold with a release...I applied a light wipe of olive oil with a cue tip (inspired by http://sugru.com/gurus/categories/sugru-hacks/topics/repaired-audio-plug-on-earbuds). Press sugru into the bottom of the mold, so that it fills the entire cavity. Press the top of the mold into place and compress. I used a pair of small clamps. Wait for the sugru to cure...it'll take a while. I opened the mold after 24 hours for me in a 65 F room but the parts were somewhat soft. I left the top of the mold off for another day then removed the feet without problem. They feel pretty solid now.

title: Printrbot Simple 2014 Print and System Cooling

description.text:
We have designed a mounting bracket and shroud for an 80mm fan to cool the Printrbot Simple 2014 extruder motor. This will solve the problem of having soft PLA filament getting jammed in-between the extruder gear and the alu-extruder due to excessive heat from the extruder motor. The extruder cooling system consists of 3 parts (the shroud, the shroud bracket, and the fan bracket). First install the shroud bracket around the alu-extuder. It snap fits on to the surrounding wood support and uses one of the existing bolts on the back (it is a tight fit so install slowly with some pressure required). Next, click the shroud onto the bracket and secure with an optional small screw (the tabs on the shroud bracket may need to be gently squeezed together in order to click the shroud on). Lastly, install an 80mm fan onto the back of the shroud and attach the fan bracket to the top back screw on the fan. Secure the bracket to your Simple using the existing bolt on top of the wooden extruder mount. We found a 12V 80mm fan that only drew 200 mA so we tied it into the existing 40mm print cooling fan connection.
We also designed a matching and (we believe) more effective print cooling fan shroud. It is a straight replacement for the factor cooling shroud just be sure to tap the 4 mounting holes using the bolts before installing because the fit is a little tight.
If you have any questions or comments please let us know and be sure to check us out at http://www.jrpi.ca.
NOTE: SketchUp design files are included if anyone wants to modify/tweak this design.
Timelapse of the system in action printing our 40mm cooling fan shroud: http://youtu.be/HbhIOHCUFMs
Video of the system components: http://youtu.be/NEwHKKXoB7o

Print the shroud bracket with supports as there are 90 degree overhangs within this part. All other parts do not require support. We printed at standard quality (0.2mm layer, 15% infill) and are happy with the results.
See the installation instructions in the description.

comments.text:
It looks like a clean design but there is very little surface area for the heat to escape across.
I just put an old CPU heatsink on top of the extruder stepper motor and it seems to have resolved the problem altogether.
With a fan that size if you incorporate a heat sink you'll probably run very cool.

I just used the mounting bracket and zip tied the fan to it.  Keeps the extruder cool and no more filament jams.  :-)  Also, do NOT tie your fan power into the existing hotend fan. title: Customizable blimp for embossing or dualstrusion

description.text:
It's an advertising blimp!
The OpenSCAD file is included, so you can customize it with your own message. You can export for dualstrusion, with the windows and letters in a different color from the hull, or embossed, if you only have a single extruder.

The included STL files have the blimp with the Makerbot name on the sides. (The photos are of a printed blimp with my son's name on it.) If you want the embossed version, print the files blimp_mb_e_front and blimp_mb_e_back, and stick them together. If you want the dualstrusion version, merge the blimp_mb_d_hull_front and blimp_mb_d_deco_front together, and print them. Do the same with the corresponding files for the back. You might be able to print the embossed version with zero infill, but the dualstrusion version I think needs some infill, to support the letters which are quite deeply recessed. To customize the blimp, you will need a font from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:13677. I'm currently using Orbitron_Bold, which is awesome. You can use whatever font you like, just make sure to change the include statement, and then the two uses of the font in the module thetext, immediately below. Open the OpenSCAD file personal blimp v1, and at the very beginning, you'll see a constant name that you can set to your text. Just below it, in module thetext, you will see two commented lines where you can set the Z offset for the text on each side. Press F5 to refresh to see how your model will look. When everything is to your liking, go to the very end of the SCAD file, and you'll see a bunch of calls to different modules, all commented out. You should comment out the module in the section labelled "plain ship", and then uncomment the appropriate sections and render them using F6, and then export to STL. For a dualstrusion ship, you'll need to separately render the hull front & back, and the deco front & back. For an embossed ship, you'll need to render the hull front and back only, from the embossed section. If you don't want a message on the side, you can just print the front and back half in the plain ship section, but who wants that? For extra credit, it's the module thetext that is combined with the hull to either dualstrude or emboss, anything you put in there will work, so you can extrude a DXF logo, add shapes, etc.
